				\begin{document}$$ {P}_{heat}={P}_{elec.}-{P}_{opt.}={I}_f{XV}_f-\frac{{\mathrm{\O}}_v}{Wpot.} $$\end{document}where Pelec. is the injected electrical power; Pheat and Popt. are the generated heat energy and optical power after the input power is injected, respectively; If and Vf are the drive current and forward voltage at LED operating conditions, respectively; Øv is the total luminous flux; and Wopt is the luminous efficacy of optical radiation (LER) of the LEDs. The primary reason for the difference in the surface temperature of these packages is the difference in their thermal conductivity coefficients: 1.05 W/mK for liquid-type samples, which are composed of glass, and 0.185–0.196 W/mK for the dispensing samples, which are composed of PMMA. The glass container of the liquid-type samples facilitates heat dissipation and thus has a high luminous efficiency. Thus, improving the heat dissipation characteristics of the samples can enhance the photon output.
